A.4.4 Outlier handling (robust & explainable)

In[590]:
def clip_outliers(series, lower_q=0.01, upper_q=0.99):
    lower = series.quantile(lower_q)
    upper = series.quantile(upper_q)
    return series.clip(lower, upper)
In[591]:
#Apply Clipping 
for col in numeric_sensor_cols:
    df_clean[col] = clip_outliers(df_clean[col])

A.4.5 Encode categorical variables

In[593]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

le_device = LabelEncoder()
df_clean["device_encoded"] = le_device.fit_transform(df_clean["device"])

A.4.6 Feature scaling (CRITICAL for ML)

In[595]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

scaler = StandardScaler()

scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(df_clean[numeric_sensor_cols])

df_scaled = pd.DataFrame(
    scaled_features,
    columns=[f"{c}_scaled" for c in numeric_sensor_cols]
)

df_clean = pd.concat([df_clean.reset_index(drop=True), df_scaled], axis=1)

Task D.2 Central Limit Theorem (CLT)

In[700]:
data = df["temp"].values
np.random.seed(42)  # reproducibility

sample_size = 50       # size of each sample
num_samples = 1000     # number of samples

sample_means = []

for _ in range(num_samples):
    sample = np.random.choice(data, size=sample_size, replace=True)
    sample_means.append(sample.mean())

sample_means = np.array(sample_means)

#Effect of sample size (small vs large)
def generate_sample_means(data, sample_size, num_samples=1000):
    return [
        np.random.choice(data, size=sample_size, replace=True).mean()
        for _ in range(num_samples)
    ]
means_small = generate_sample_means(data, sample_size=5)
means_large = generate_sample_means(data, sample_size=100)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.hist(means_small, bins=40)
plt.title("Sample Size = 5")

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.hist(means_large, bins=40)
plt.title("Sample Size = 100")

plt.show()

Task D.3 Statistical Confidence & Estimation

In[705]:
#Confidence interval for mean (temperature)
from scipy import stats
temp_data = df["temp"].values
n = len(temp_data)
mean_temp = temp_data.mean()
std_temp = temp_data.std(ddof=1)

confidence = 0.95
alpha = 1 - confidence

t_critical = stats.t.ppf(1 - alpha/2, df=n-1)

ci_lower = mean_temp - t_critical * std_temp / np.sqrt(n)
ci_upper = mean_temp + t_critical * std_temp / np.sqrt(n)

mean_temp, ci_lower, ci_upper
Out[705]:
(22.459124756525938, 22.450971749868604, 22.467277763183272)
In[706]:
#Visualize confidence interval
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 2))
plt.errorbar(mean_temp, 0, xerr=[[mean_temp - ci_lower], [ci_upper - mean_temp]], 
             fmt='o')
plt.yticks([])
plt.title("95% Confidence Interval for Mean Temperature")
plt.xlabel("Temperature")
plt.show()
In[707]:
#Confidence interval for probability (motion)
p_hat = df["motion"].mean()
n = len(df)

z = stats.norm.ppf(0.975)  # 95% CI

ci_lower_p = p_hat - z * np.sqrt((p_hat * (1 - p_hat)) / n)
ci_upper_p = p_hat + z * np.sqrt((p_hat * (1 - p_hat)) / n)

p_hat, ci_lower_p, ci_upper_p

Task E.2 Baseline Model (Linear Regression)

In[715]:
def regression_metrics(y_true, y_pred):
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred))
    r2 = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)
    return mae, rmse, r2
In[716]:

In[764]:
#Effect size
def cohens_d(a, b):
    a = np.array(a); b = np.array(b)
    n1, n2 = len(a), len(b)
    s1, s2 = a.var(ddof=1), b.var(ddof=1)
    s_pooled = ((n1 - 1)*s1 + (n2 - 1)*s2) / (n1 + n2 - 2)
    return (a.mean() - b.mean()) / np.sqrt(s_pooled)

d = cohens_d(temp_motion1, temp_motion0)
print("Cohen's d (motion=1 minus motion=0):", d)

Cohen's d (motion=1 minus motion=0): 1.1069837108430172
